args: Catherine? It's Julietta. Would you\ncare to join me for afternoon tea?
Oh, Lady Julietta. No, thank you.\nI am quite sated and do not—
It's only natural that you are hungry—\nyou've been holed up in your room\nsince yesterday, after all.
Tea is a lady's favorite time of the day.\nSurely you share that notion?
Mmm... The leaves are fine today,\nand the bergamot smells delightful.
N-no, it is delightful. The scones pair\nquite well with it and...
Er, is this not the sort of conversation\nyou were hoping for?
You said you needed to be smarter\nabout choosing your friends.
I thought you looked to interact with\npeople from families similar to yours.\nWas I mistaken?
People are naturally sensitive to\ndifferences in station.
But those of the same standing who were\nraised with similar environments and\nexpectations have no such concerns.
I... I wanted to find someone who truly\nunderstood me. Someone who looked\nat me for who I AM, not my family.
Oh, I'm sure there are many things I would\nrelate to with you...
But would your true friends not understand\nyou better than I ever could?
I thought so, once—but then I heard them\nsay the kinds of things that live on the\ntongues of everyone else:
＂Because you're the mayor's daughter.＂\n＂Because you're rich.＂
I once believed Sandy and Becky were\nthe only ones who saw past my station.\nBut now...?
They were the first friends\nI could truly open up to.
...Didja hear? Catherine scored first place\nin her grade on the exams this time, too.\nShe really IS perfect!
Yeah, well, I heard a rumor she\nasked Daddy to fix her grades.
Oh my gosh, that is SUCH a rich person\nthing to do. How disgusting!
Impressive, Catherine. Your grades\nhave walloped mine yet again.
And you both believe I earned it?
There is a scurrilous rumor about\nthat I am having my father use his\nposition and wealth to fix my grades.
Whaaat! Come on, Cat, that's bunk.
Exactly. We know your grades are the\nresults of hard work and nothing else.
Oh! P-pardon me...\nThese fickle allergies are just...
Wait, are you seriously so happy to be\ntop of the class that you're crying?
Wh-what? Of course not!\nI expected nothing less!
...I wanted to give myself some sort of\nvalue. Something that would shine brighter\nthan my status as someone's daughter.
So I worked hard at all that I did—\nstudying, martial arts, social skills...\nEverything had to be perfect.
And I thought it had worked.\nI thought my two friends saw me for\nsomething other than some rich kid.
But I suppose that was a fantasy as well,\nfor I was never even close to perfect.
And without perfection, what merits\nare there to being my friend besides\nmy social standing?
...You're just arbitrarily concluding how\nothers will value you.
I went through this same thing, you know.
I was terrified of falling short of \nexpectations and disappointing people.\nThe pain of it consumed my life.
But on the day my false bravado was\nexposed, my friends were still there.
They even went so far as to compliment\nme and say I was an excellent Paladyn \nwhen I thought myself utterly useless.
In the end, it is up to the individual\nto find value in things.
What sort of things did your friends\nseek value in? Status? Perfection?
Who, Sandy and Becky? No, they...
They knew how hard I worked.
Then your status and perfection—or even a\nlack thereof—won't mean a thing to them.
But then why would they say...?
You'll never know until you ask.
I'm sure you'll find the\nperfect way to do it.
Eugene? I thought you had\nreturned to Quinbell!
Yeah, but I had to come back!
Sandy and Becky are in trouble!
